  16. (** Processor-native integers.

  18.    This module provides operations on the type [nativeint] of
  19.    signed 32-bit integers (on 32-bit platforms) or
  20.    signed 64-bit integers (on 64-bit platforms).
  21.    This integer type has exactly the same width as that of a
  22.    pointer type in the C compiler.  All arithmetic operations over
  23.    [nativeint] are taken modulo 2{^32} or 2{^64} depending
  24.    on the word size of the architecture.

  26.    Performance notice: values of type [nativeint] occupy more memory
  27.    space than values of type [int], and arithmetic operations on
  28.    [nativeint] are generally slower than those on [int].  Use [nativeint]
  29.    only when the application requires the extra bit of precision
  30.    over the [int] type.

  32.     Literals for native integers are suffixed by n:
  33.     {[
  34.      let zero: nativeint = 0n
  35.      let one: nativeint = 1n
  36.      let m_one: nativeint = -1n
  37.     ]}
  38. *)

  74. external rem : nativeint -> nativeint -> nativeint = "%nativeint_mod"
  75. (** Integer remainder.  If [y] is not zero, the result
  76.    of [Nativeint.rem x y] satisfies the following properties:
  77.    [Nativeint.zero <= Nativeint.rem x y < Nativeint.abs y] and
  78.    [x = Nativeint.add (Nativeint.mul (Nativeint.div x y) y)
  79.                       (Nativeint.rem x y)].
  80.    If [y = 0], [Nativeint.rem x y] raises [Division_by_zero]. *)

  82. val unsigned_rem : nativeint -> nativeint -> nativeint
  83. (** Same as {!rem}, except that arguments and result are interpreted as {e
  84.     unsigned} native integers.

  86.     @since 4.08 *)

  88. val succ : nativeint -> nativeint
  89. (** Successor.
  90.    [Nativeint.succ x] is [Nativeint.add x Nativeint.one]. *)

  92. val pred : nativeint -> nativeint
  93. (** Predecessor.

  96. val abs : nativeint -> nativeint
  97. (** [abs x] is the absolute value of [x]. On [min_int] this
  98.    is [min_int] itself and thus remains negative. *)

  100. val size : int
  101. (** The size in bits of a native integer.  This is equal to [32]
  102.    on a 32-bit platform and to [64] on a 64-bit platform. *)

  104. val max_int : nativeint
  105. (** The greatest representable native integer,
  106.    either 2{^31} - 1 on a 32-bit platform,
  107.    or 2{^63} - 1 on a 64-bit platform. *)

  109. val min_int : nativeint
  110. (** The smallest representable native integer,

  112.    or -2{^63} on a 64-bit platform. *)

  126. external shift_left : nativeint -> int -> nativeint = "%nativeint_lsl"
  127. (** [Nativeint.shift_left x y] shifts [x] to the left by [y] bits.
  128.    The result is unspecified if [y < 0] or [y >= bitsize],
  129.    where [bitsize] is [32] on a 32-bit platform and
  130.    [64] on a 64-bit platform. *)

  132. external shift_right : nativeint -> int -> nativeint = "%nativeint_asr"
  133. (** [Nativeint.shift_right x y] shifts [x] to the right by [y] bits.
  134.    This is an arithmetic shift: the sign bit of [x] is replicated
  135.    and inserted in the vacated bits.
  136.    The result is unspecified if [y < 0] or [y >= bitsize]. *)

  138. external shift_right_logical :
  139.   nativeint -> int -> nativeint = "%nativeint_lsr"
  140. (** [Nativeint.shift_right_logical x y] shifts [x] to the right
  141.    by [y] bits.
  142.    This is a logical shift: zeroes are inserted in the vacated bits
  143.    regardless of the sign of [x].
  144.    The result is unspecified if [y < 0] or [y >= bitsize]. *)

  163. external of_float : float -> nativeint

  165.   [@@unboxed] [@@noalloc]
  166. (** Convert the given floating-point number to a native integer,
  167.    discarding the fractional part (truncate towards 0).
  168.    If the truncated floating-point number is outside the range

  181. external to_int32 : nativeint -> int32 = "%nativeint_to_int32"
  182. (** Convert the given native integer to a
  183.    32-bit integer (type [int32]).  On 64-bit platforms,
  184.    the 64-bit native integer is taken modulo 2{^32},
  185.    i.e. the top 32 bits are lost.  On 32-bit platforms,
  186.    the conversion is exact. *)

  188. external of_string : string -> nativeint = "caml_nativeint_of_string"
  189. (** Convert the given string to a native integer.
  190.    The string is read in decimal (by default, or if the string
  191.    begins with [0u]) or in hexadecimal, octal or binary if the
  192.    string begins with [0x], [0o] or [0b] respectively.

  194.    The [0u] prefix reads the input as an unsigned integer in the range
  195.    [[0, 2*Nativeint.max_int+1]].  If the input exceeds {!Nativeint.max_int}
  196.    it is converted to the signed integer
  197.    [Int64.min_int + input - Nativeint.max_int - 1].

  199.    @raise Failure if the given string is not
  200.    a valid representation of an integer, or if the integer represented
  201.    exceeds the range of integers representable in type [nativeint]. *)
